# A NOTE ON STATISTICAL ANALYSIS METHOD CHOICES AND TRADEOFFS

# We first analyze the relationship between dependent and independent variables (as specified in the hypotheses below) using
# traditional linear modeling and generalized linear modeling with heteroskedasticity correction, as is common for cross-sectional data of this nature.
# These models use dummy variables for each category of independent categorical values that don't have many categories.
# In cases where independent categorical values have many categories (>35), we follow the advice of the statistical literature to convert them to continuous numerical
# variables as it is highly unlikely that any difference would be significant and it drastically improves itnerpretability and adjusts for uneven design bias.

# While it is theoretically expected that the continuous dependent variables "days_to/from..." will be correlated as they are included within one another
# we note that there is a very large difference in n between days_to_resolution and both days_to_first_assignment days_from_first_assignment_to_resolution
# The latter two only have definition if a bug is assigned at all, which only happens around 1/7th of the time in the data set.
# Further, their treatment as independent by using them as control models at the same time is likely to be spurious as the data
# has shown to sometimes duplicate bug counts because of the manner in which each one was operationalized.
# As observed and detailed in the data_operationalization section, the result of the operationalization choices made was a tradeoff
# between comparability of these three variables to one another and promoting independent measurement of differenting underlying constructs.
# The tradeoff was chosen towards the latter, which serves the present purposes of analysis quite well.
# As such, we conclude that the very large difference in n paired with the operationalization tradeoffs that resulted in indepdnent measurement of
# likely differing underlying constructs will account for a sufficient amount of colinearity in the dependent variables that
# it can be addressed via post-hoc validation. Therefore, we focus on ANCOVA modeling at the bug-level rather than MANCOVA and do not include them
# as control variables when another one is dependent variable and only one of the three will be included as control variable to
# match the related discrete outcome variable in the logistic models that follow
# An added benefit is that this approach is more common in traditional peer-reviewed top management journals and hence more familiar to readers

# We follow the advice of Fox (2008) and Fox & Weisberg (2011) [See ?Anova] to select type II sum of squares ANOVA modeling
# It maintains interpretability of main effects for hypotheses testing, as desired, while also correcting for the unbalanced nature
# of the factor-based predictors in the model
# Further, the Anova() function in the R package car (see ?car) allows for heteroskedasticity correction in the model in a single step, compensating
# for some of the non-linearity of the data discussed earlier

# We create three models for each dependent variable:
#	1) [Control test model]	Including only all the theoretically related control variables to test their effect on the dependent variable
#	2) [Control only model]	Including only the significant control variables that were shown to have an effect on the dependent variable
#   3) [Full model]			Including the independent variables related to the hypotheses and the significant control variables

# The significant control and full models are analyzed as both linear/generalized linear models with dummy variables and as ANCOVA models to
# provide analytical triangulation and improve interpretability
# Numerous comparative statistics are calculated to show the relative impact of the full model above and beyond the control model in each case


